The Manger-constellation (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Φάτνη</SPAN>) which Aratus associates with storm. Panope, the reading in <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G</SPAN>, being a fine-weather divinity, is unsuitable here.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: The Manger, or <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Φάτνη</SPAN>, was already in Antiquity more commonly called by the name we've retained, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Cancer</SPAN>; see Allen's <I>Star Names</I>,
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Topics/astronomy/_Texts/secondary/ALLSTA/Cancer*.html#Manger
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
p113</A>.
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note17" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">17</A>
The Great Bear.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note18" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref18
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">18</A>
In man's quest for gold and silver, regions of earth are "put to the torture" by the processes of mining and smelting until they buy themselves off by the ore they have yielded (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sese pretio redimant</SPAN>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note19" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref19
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">19</A>
<I>i.e.</I> the rest is silence after the truth (<I>i.e.</I> where their hidden treasures lie) has been extorted from them: <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tacent</SPAN> gives a better contrast than <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">iacent</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note20" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref20
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">20</A>
The two similes illustrate from mechanical examples the theory of the action of water and air in Aetna. In the first example, the readings suggested give a choice among a variety of contrivances. If <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ora</SPAN> is read, the Siren-like horn might be on the sea-shore, or on the Tiber-bank during one of Julius Caesar's <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">naumachiae</SPAN>, or at Lake Fucinus when the emperor Claudius exhibited a naval spectacle in <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> 53
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Claudius*.html#21.6
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Suet. <I>Claud.</I> xxi)</A>. If <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">duci</SPAN> were a certain correction and if it were then clear that only Claudius were meant, the passage would assist (as some have tried to make it assist) in dating the poem. The reading <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">hora</SPAN> implies a hydraulic time-machine for announcing the hour to gods or men (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">deo</SPAN>?, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">deis</SPAN>?, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">duci</SPAN>?). Ellis's <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">urna</SPAN> is meant to denote a hydraulic vessel fitted to work the "Triton." The second comparison is concerned with a


<A ID="p387x"></A>hydraulic organ of a sort known in Rome from Cicero's time (<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/tusc3.shtml#43
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Tusc. Disp.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.18 (43)</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">hydrauli hortabere ut audiat voces potius quam Platonis?</SPAN> <I>i.e.</I> "will you advise him to listen to the notes of water-organ rather than to the words of Plato?"). The invention is ascribed to Ctesibius, a barber of Alexandria, <I>circ.</I> 200 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> Nero was almost madly interested in water-organs (Suet. <I>Nero</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Nero*.html#41
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">xli
	</A>
and
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Nero*.html#54
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
liv</A>).

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: The idea that water under pressure is the cause of volcanic action may have suggested itself to our writer from the powerful geysers of hot water that erupt from Mt. Etna. The fact that he himself doesn't mention these striking sights — although they were well known in Antiquity (<A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_ae09.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 9<BR>of Vergil\'s <I>Aeneid</I>'+Lat2+LatSearch+'Palici</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Aeneid</I>, 9.585</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/11D*.html#89
	"TARGET="Diodorus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Diodorus,WIDTH,185)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Diodorus, <SPAN CLASS="small">XI</SPAN>.89</A>;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Macrobius/Saturnalia/5*.html#19.15
	"TARGET="Macrobius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Macrobius, <I>Sat.</I> 5.19.15 ff.</A>), would have buttressed his argument, and would have afforded him an opportunity for poetic display — suggests to me that he is not writing first-hand.
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note21" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref21
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21</A>
<I>i.e.</I> probably with a pedal. A mosaic found near Trier last century gives a representation of a water-organ (Wilmovsky, <I>Röm. Villa zu Nennig</I>, Bonn, 1864‑65). There the position of the organ-player is consistent with his using his hands to play and his feet on a pedal to set the water in motion. In May 1931, a handsome hydraulic organ dating from <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> 288 was discovered at Aquincum on the Danube, the capital of Lower Pannonia (now Alt-Ofen, part of Buda Pest).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note22" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref22
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">22</A>
307‑329. The reasoning takes the form of an answer to a possible objector who agrees that there may be causes for winds in Aetna other than those already set forth (283‑306). The argument is that you must allow that rock-falls <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground generate air-currents; and, just as river vapours in valleys emit air (more perceptibly in hot climates, Munro says here; <I>cf.</I> also
Lucret. <SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.476 <I>sqq.</I>), so the effect of moisture (<I>cf.</I> <A ID="p389x"></A>the clouds of 290‑293) within confined caverns <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground must be far more potent. Two analogies are cited — waves under strong gales and the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">siphon</SPAN> forcing water on burning houses.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note23" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref23
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">23</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Sipo</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sipho</SPAN>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sifo</SPAN> = <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">σίφων</SPAN>) was the tube of a fire-engine used to pump up water.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
330‑358. This passage aims at disproving the idea that the wind which in an eruption issues from the crater has been constantly entering the mountain by the same avenue. Two arguments refute the notion: (1) the cloud which hangs invariably over the summit would be displaced by any wind <A ID="p391x"></A>passing down the crater; (2) the custom of worshippers to assemble at the crater and there offer incense would be impossible, if there were powerful winds blowing into the mountain. This, then, is ocular evidence of calm against any theory that winds from without cause volcanic explosions.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note25" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref25
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">25</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">opus</SPAN> here is not much more than "condition." It implies the activity, actual or latent, of the mountain, its "working": <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#142
	"TARGET="Aetna"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">142</A>,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#188
	"TARGET="Aetna"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
188</A>,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#219
	"TARGET="Aetna"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
219</A>,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#277
	"TARGET="Aetna"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
277</A>,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#566
	"TARGET="Aetna"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
566</A>. An alternative sense would be "fabric," "formation" as in <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#257
	"TARGET="Aetna"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">257</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note26" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A>
The passage is difficult. Taking <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ut</SPAN> with Birt and Sudhaus as "how," we may paraphrase it: "noting the calm on Aetna's summit, you can understand how the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">spiritus</SPAN>, so powerful when roused, fails to displace any part of the crater (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">arcu</SPAN>) when quiescent." [Sudhaus renders "von dem Felsrande des Kraters," but <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">arcu</SPAN>, if the right reading, may mean an arched cavern and not the crater-curve.] Ellis propounds a different view, suggesting that <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">huicne credis ut numquam diripiat</SPAN> may mean "Can you believe, on the showing of this, the impossibility of the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">spiritus</SPAN>, when in a milder form, tearing down masses of rock?"


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note27" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref27
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">27</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ventilat ignem</SPAN>,
	<A HREF="
https://www.curculio.org/Juvenal/s03.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Juvenal\'s 3d Satire'+Lat2+LatSearch+'cursu</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Juv. <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.253</A>:<A CLASS="comment"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('Note the different verb in the online version.')"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.curculio.org/Juvenal/s01.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Juvenal\'s 1st Satire'+Lat2+LatSearch+'digitis</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ventilet aurum</SPAN> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.28</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note28" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">28</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_ge04.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 4<BR>of the Georgics'+Lat2+LatSearch+'tenui labor</SPAN>.')"
onMouseOut="nd();">Virg. <I>G.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.6</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">in tenui labor</SPAN>. The connexion of


<A ID="p393x"></A>thought is not easy to follow. It has just been claimed that even powerful volcanic agencies may elude notice (349‑350); and the parallel is cited of the air-current made by the priest in his lustration striking the worshippers' faces without their being aware of the impact. <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Corpora</SPAN> = "atoms"; <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">nostris</SPAN> = "our human bodies," which suffer the impact of atoms of air unconsciously. The extremely condensed <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">adeo in tenui vim causa repellit</SPAN> is literally "in so slight an instance a cause repels force," <I>i.e.</I> keeps it from being felt. The "slight instance" is the priestly sprinkling of water and his waving the lustral fire: "force" may be said to be "repelled," if it is not allowed free play, and the worshippers are apparently unconscious of its operation. The proper explanation of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">causa</SPAN> is obscure, and Ellis may be right in suspecting a lacuna after <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">repellit</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note29" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">29</A>
<I>i.e.</I> on Aetna's summit between eruptions.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note30" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">adoratis</SPAN>, "venerated," the reading of <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">C</SPAN>, makes quite good sense.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Silvae</SPAN>, "materials" = Greek <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ὕλη</SPAN> in the sense of "mass," "stuff." The plural here is noticeable.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A>
The accus. and infin. construction <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">materiam discurrere</SPAN> depends on a verb implied in <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">crispantur</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note33" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">33</A>
Springs of water at the foot of Aetna with a sulphurous or bituminous taste testify to the presence of inflammable substances in the mountain. The author proceeds (398‑425) to argue that stones which liquefy, especially the lava-stone (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">lapis molaris</SPAN>) point to the same conclusion. Though a chief


<A ID="p397x"></A>cause of volcanic conflagration, the lava-stone externally does not look inflammable; if struck, however, with an iron bar, it gives off sparks, and in a powerful furnace is more quickly fusible than iron. Its great characteristic is its stubborn retention of fire: this marks it off from other substances which, once burnt out, cannot be rekindled.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A>
There is an apparent inconsistency between l. 412 and the statements of 418 and 422 <I>sqq.</I> The partial burning of successive eruptions (422‑423) is to be contrasted with a complete burning out of the lava-stone (411‑412 and 424‑425); or


<A ID="p399x"></A>it may be that 412 implies only an <I>immediate</I> return to former strength.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A>
Monte Epomeo (Latin <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Epopeus</SPAN>), the chief mountain of Ischia (Latin <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Aenaria</SPAN>) has been noted for sudden outbreaks.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">locus</SPAN> = Solfatara. Its character in antiquity is described by Lucretius (<SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.747‑8),
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/5D*.html#T246a
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Strabo 246 (= <SPAN CLASS="small">V</SPAN>.4.6 <I>ad fin.</I>)
	</A>
and Petronius, <I>Satyr.</I> 120, line 67 <I>sqq.</I>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Rotunda</SPAN> is a translation of <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">στρογγύλη</SPAN>, the Greek name represented by the modern Stromboli.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A>
Trachytic lava, not the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">lapis molaris</SPAN> of Aetna.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A>
In the Lipari islands Vulcano (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Ἱερὰ `Ἡφαίστου</SPAN>) is the southernmost, as Stromboli is the northernmost.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A>
or "to act the counterfeit witness."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/36*.html#137
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plin. <I>N. H.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XXXVI</SPAN>.137</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">molarem quidam pyriten vocant</SPAN>:
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#404
	"TARGET="Grattius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Grattius, <I>Cyn.</I> 404</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">vivum lapidem</SPAN>. The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">lapis molaris</SPAN> is appropriately called <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pyrites</SPAN>, "firestone" (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">πυρίτης</SPAN>) or <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">vivus lapis</SPAN>, "the live stone," in virtue of its characteristic conservation of fire: <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#note33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">note on 395</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A>
There may be a lacuna after <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">minatur</SPAN> (462) as Munro thought, and there must be a lacuna after <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ictaque ramis</SPAN> (463), if that is the right reading.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note43" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">43</A>
The Simaethus or Symaethus in Eastern Sicily drains a considerable part of the island. The impetuosity of the lava-flood, carrying it over the bed of the river, is contrasted with the rigid immobility which marks it when solidified (507‑510). The hard masses are described as lying immovable for twenty days together, blocking the river. D'Orville preferred to read <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pedes</SPAN> "buried twenty feet in the ground."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note44" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A>
The editorial <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">externa immotus</SPAN> meets the difficulty of finding a noun to agree with <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">externam</SPAN> (either substituted in the text for <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">etiam</SPAN>, or understood like <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">materiam</SPAN> or <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">naturam</SPAN>). <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Externa refellit</SPAN> = "refutes the idea of alien substances," though the object of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">refellere</SPAN> is usually a person or such a word as <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">verbum</SPAN>


<A ID="p409x"></A>or <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">mendacium</SPAN>. <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Immotus color</SPAN> leads up to <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">una operis facies eadem</SPAN> in 529; and the awkward <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">multis</SPAN> disappears. For metrical parallel see <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#479
	"TARGET="Aetna"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
479</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>
Scaliger based his suggestion of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">rhytas</SPAN> on <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ῥυτός</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ῥεῖν</SPAN>) "flowing," "fluid," hence applicable to fusible substances.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note46" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref46
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">46</A>
Heraclitus of Ephesus, one of the early Ionian philosophers, held that heat is the inherent principle of existence and that everything is in a perpetual flux. By the obscurity of his writings on physics he earned the name of "the dark" (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">σκοτεινός</SPAN>).<!-- COPHP -->


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note47" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A>
The mythological allusions in lines 574‑579 are to the miraculous building of Thebes when the stones obeyed the call of the "pious" brethren Amphion and Zethus; the never-ending hatred of Eteocles and Polynices, the sons of Oedipus, shown in the separation of even the flames on their altar; the seven champions who marched from Argos upon Thebes; the gulf in the earth which swallowed Amphiaraus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note48" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">48</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">piis</SPAN>: Amphion and Zethus are called <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pii</SPAN>, not because they fortified Thebes, but because they avenged on Dirce her maltreatment of their mother Antiope. To furnish Thebes with walls and towers Zethus brought up the stones with his strong arms, and Amphion fitted them together by the music of his lyre.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note49" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49</A>
Eurotas was the river of Sparta and Lycurgus her legendary lawgiver.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note50" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref50
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">50</A>
The three hundred Spartans who laid down their lives fighting against the Persians in the pass at Thermopylae, 480 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note51" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref51
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">51</A>
Athens is called "Cecropian" after her legendary king Cecrops. Athene (identified with Minerva) by her gift of the olive won the land belonging to Athens and so ousted Poseidon. The marble sculptures in the western pediment of the Parthenon recorded this rivalry.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note52" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref52
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">52</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21‑22 <I>supra</I>
	</A>
for another reference to Theseus' return from Crete.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note53" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref53
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">53</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Vestra</SPAN> ("of you and yours") alludes to her father Icar(i)us and the faithful hound which became Sirius. Erigone hanged herself for grief at her father's death. The theme was treated in a once celebrated poem by Eratosthenes.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note54" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref54
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">54</A>
Procne, wife of the Thracian king Tereus, avenged his violation of her sister Philomela by slaying their son Itys or Itylus and serving his flesh to Tereus as food. Legend changed Philomela into a nightingale, Procne into a swallow.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note55" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref55
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">55</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">suo Hectore</SPAN> <I>sc.</I> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">exstincto</SPAN>. Either (1) instrumental ablat., "through their Hector," he being by his death the cause of their destruction or (2) ablat. absolute, "their Hector having been destroyed": see Munro's note (which cites Cic. <I>Pro Mil.</I> 47, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">iacent suis testibus</SPAN>, "they are prostrated by the evidence of their own witnesses,") and Th. Maguire's discussion, <I>Journal of Philology</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN> (1871), pp232 <I>sqq.</I>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note56" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref56
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">56</A>
The picture meant is the Venus Anadyomene by Apelles.


<A ID="p415x"></A>The traditional treatment of the tresses survives to some extent in Botticelli's "Nascita di Venere."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note57" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref57
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">57</A>
The Medea of Timomachus (3rd cent. <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>), a celebrated picture in which the painter represented the mother deliberating whether she should kill her children to revenge herself on Jason.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note58" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref58
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">58</A>
The masterpiece of Timanthes (about 400 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>) in which he painted the sacrifice of Iphigenia, expressing woe on the faces of the bystanders, but veiling the face of the grief-stricken father, Agamemnon. The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cerva</SPAN>, according to one form of the legend, was at the last moment miraculously substituted for the victim.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note59" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref59
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">59</A>
The bronze cow by Myron, a greatly admired work (Cic. <I>Verr.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.<SPAN CLASS="smaller">LX</SPAN>.135)<!--</A>CICERO:VERRINES-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note60" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref60
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">60</A>
The eruption was historic. Aelian, quoted in Stobaeus' <I>Florilegium</I>, 79, 38, p456 (Gaisford)<!-- STOBAEUS: FLOR -->, places it in Olympiad <A ID="p417x"></A>81 (= 456‑453 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>). He gives the names of the Catanaean youths who saved their parents from the flames as Philonomos and Kallias: <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#note62
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">n. on 629 <I>infra</I></A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note61" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref61
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">61</A>
616‑618. The satire at the expense of those who try to save their goods at the risk of life culminates in the glance at a poet struggling under a load of his own works. There is also a satiric undertone in the picture of tourists (569‑600), who are curious sightseers rather than students of nature.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note62" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref62
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">62</A>
Claudian,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Claudian/Carmina_Minora*/17.html
	"TARGET="Claudian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Carmina Minora</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">XVII</SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="small">L</SPAN>)</A>, has an elegiac poem on the statues of the two brothers, Amphinomus and Anapius at Catina now Catania. For allusions to their <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pietas</SPAN> <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/6B*.html#T269a
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Strabo, <SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.2.3 (C. 269)</A>, who calls the second brother Anapias; Sen. <I>Benef.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.37.2<!--</A>SENECA:DE BENEFICIIS-->;
	<A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lspost01/Martialis/mar_ep07.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 7<BR>of the Epigrams of Martial'+Lat2+LatSearch+'siculos</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Martial, <SPAN CLASS="small">VII</SPAN>.24.5</A>;
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/silius/silius14.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 14<BR>of Silius Italicus'+Lat2+LatSearch+'pios</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Sil. Ital. <SPAN CLASS="small">XIV</SPAN>.197</A>.
	<A HREF="
http://www.theoi.com/Text/HyginusFabulae5.html#254
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Hyginus, <I>Fab.</I> 254</A>, gives them different names. Their heads appear on both Sicilian and Roman coins, <I>e.g.</I> Head, <I>Hist. Num.</I> 117; <I>Brit. Mus. Cat.</I>

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
Thayer's Note: Possibly earlier than any of those passages,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aristotle/de_Mirabilibus*.html#154
	"TARGET="Aristotle_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusG)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
ps‑Aristotle, <I>Mirab.</I> 154</A>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note63" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref63
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">63</A>
Ditis (more commonly Dis in the nominative) is Pluto, god of the <SPAN CLASS="whole">under-world</SPAN>.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Note:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Erigone" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aetna/text*.html#ref:Erigone
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Sidus</SPAN> can mean "star", but frequently means "constellation", as in this case. The reference is to Virgo, commonly called Erigone in Antiquity: see the citations in Allen's <I>Star Names</I>,
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Topics/astronomy/_Texts/secondary/ALLSTA/Virgo*.html#Erigone
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
p461</A>; the first passage linked there, in Vergil's 1st Georgic, is particularly clear (and calls Libra a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sidus</SPAN>, too).



